## Plan: Add `mistral-instruct-v3` Specialized Chat Template Handler

**Only one file changes:** `common/chat.cpp`

### What & Why

The codebase has two template dispatch paths. The modern one is the **Jinja/specialized path** in `common/chat.cpp`, which includes `common_chat_try_specialized_template` — a chain of pattern checks on the Jinja template source string that routes to dedicated C++ handlers. This is where the new handler lives. The legacy enum-based path (`src/llama-chat.h` / `src/llama-chat.cpp`) is untouched, satisfying the "do not modify the header file" constraint.

---

### Step 1 — New handler function (insert just before `common_chat_try_specialized_template`, ~line 1633)

```cpp
// Mistral Instruct v0.3 - simple [INST]/[/INST] format, system message prepended to first user turn,
// </s> appended after assistant turns, no [SYSTEM_PROMPT] / [AVAILABLE_TOOLS] / <<SYS>>.
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;

    data.prompt = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY;

    return data;
}
```

`common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl` renders the Jinja template (the template itself handles system-message prepending). `COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY` is correct because this format has no tools, no reasoning, no PEG parsing.

---

### Step 2 — Detection block (insert after GigaChatV3 check, before `return std::nullopt;`, ~line 1689)

```cpp
    // Mistral Instruct v0.3 - [INST]/[/INST] without [SYSTEM_PROMPT], [AVAILABLE_TOOLS], or <<SYS>>.
    if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]") == std::string::npos &&
        src.find("<<SYS>>") == std::string::npos) {
        LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v3\n");
        return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
    }
```

**Detection conditions and what each excludes:**
- `[INST]` present → only Mistral-family templates
- `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` absent → excludes Ministral 3 and V7
- `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]` absent → excludes Mistral-Nemo / V3-with-tools  
- `<<SYS>>` absent → excludes Llama-2 style templates

The Ministral 3 check (which requires `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`) runs first and is completely disjoint from our new check — no ordering risk.

